definition.value: The primordial vasculature that will develop into blood vessels  by the process of tubulogenesis.  The  vascular cord is composed of angioblast or vascular endothelial cells in a solid linear mass called a cord.  The cord then undergoes  tubulogenesis to form the lumen of the vessels.

An assay in which sequencing technology (e.g. Solexa/454) is used to generate RNA sequence, from the presumed non-coding transcibed regions of the genome, to analyse these and/or to quantitate transcript abundance

An assay in which sequencing technology (e.g. Solexa/454) is used to generate RNA sequence, from the presumed coding transcibed regions of the genome, or analyse these or to quantitate transcript abundance
An assay that exploits a sequencer as the instrument to find results.
An assay in which DNA is the input molecule derived from pooled clones (for example BACs and Fosmids) is sequenced using high throughput technology using shotgun methodology.
An assay in which DNA is the input molecule derived from clones which are mapped then sequenced in small fragments.
An assay in which DNA is the input molecule derived from a clone and 5',3' or both ends of a clone are sequenced
An assay in which DNA is the input molecule derived from fragmented whole genome preparation is sequenced

An assay in which DNA is the input molecule derived from chromosome or other replicon is sequenced. The random part refers to the fact the sequence can not be reliably ordered within the known chromosome.
An assay in which DNA is the input molecule derived from exons is sequenced.
An assay in which a DNA or RNA input molecule amplified by PCR is sequenced.
An assay in which DNA us the input molecule derived from cleavage of DNA by use of methylation sensitive restriction enzymes to digest genome DNA at unmethylated CpGs.
